    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Like this:</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>List&lt;String&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();\nString[] a = list.toArray(new String[0]);\n</code></pre>\n<p>Before Java 6 it was recommended to write:</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>String[] a = list.toArray(new String[list.size()]);\n</code></pre>\n<p>because the internal implementation would realloc a properly sized array anyway so you were better doing it upfront. Since Java 6 the empty array is preferred, see <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/174093\">.toArray(new MyClass[0]) or .toArray(new MyClass[myList.size()])?</a></p>\n<p>If your list is not properly typed, you need to do a cast before calling toArray. Like this:</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>List list = new ArrayList&lt;String&gt;();\nString[] a = ((List&lt;String&gt;) list).toArray(new String[list.size()]);\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
